Unit cell volume:V_{\text{cell}} = a \cdot b \cdot c \cdot \sqrt{
1 + 2\cos\alpha\cos\beta\cos\gamma \cos^2\alpha - \cos^2\beta - \cos^2\gamma
}

If the void volume of a MOF, V_{\text{void}}, is obtained via molecular simulation or adsorption experiments, the porosity \phi can be expressed as:\phi = \frac{V_{\text{void}}}{V_{\text{cell}}}

Discussion

Why do MOFs generally have a higher degree of designability than traditional porous materials such as activated carbon or silica gel?

